Originally these creatures were made by Primus, and even the most wily and secretive of traders will enter into contracts with them- nothing is more straightforward and true than the ideals that forge the Inevitable's will. Inevitables care not for intent or purpose- only for the words written in their contracts. Lethal force is used to ensure such words are stood by.

Name: Iron Man (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: J.A.R.V.I.S.: Sir, there are still terabytes of calculations needed before an actual flight is adju- Tony: J.A.R.V.I.S., sometimes you gotta run before you can walk.

Name: Iron Man Armor Model 13
Summary: Model 13 was Tony Stark's attempt of creating something new and unique compared to his previous armors. Opposed to a single, integrated suit, Model 13's structure was based on a modular component system. The armor's capabilities, powers, and equipment would be reconfigured by swapping in and out sub-systems such as boots, gloves, helmets, weapons, or scanners. The varieties of equipment and abilities Model 13 would have would be heavily dependent on the mission Tony needed to accomplish.

Name: Iron Man Armor Model 15
Summary: Tony Stark created this armor while in a mental breakdown due to the stress of attacks on Stark Enterprises and from being under Immortus' influence. This new suit would be used to betray and even kill fellow Avengers during the Crossing storyline event.

Name: Iron Man Armor Model 8
Summary: Model 8 or commonly known as the Silver Centurion Armor is one of Stark's most iconic suits. Appearing in the iconic storyline Armor Wars, this suit was made when he wanted to reinvent himself as Iron Man.

Name: Iron Man Armor Model 9
Summary: This armor was created by Tony Stark before the events of the first Armor Wars storyline, although he was reluctant to use the new armor due to its high capabilities. Tony would later be forced to use the armor against the villain Firepower after the Silver Centurion Armor was destroyed. After defeating Firepower, Tony would continue to use this armor for more missions and battles.

Name: Iron Monger (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Obadiah Stane was a wealthy financer and businessman who took interest in acquiring Stark International, using his agents to assault it and Stark's allies.

Name: Ivern
Summary: Ivern Bramblefoot, known to many as the Green Father, is a peculiar half man, half tree who roams Runeterra's forests, cultivating life everywhere he goes. He knows the secrets of the natural world, and holds deep friendships with all things that grow, fly, and scuttle. Ivern wanders the wilderness, imparting strange wisdom to any he meets, enriching the forests, and occasionally entrusting loose-lipped butterflies with his secrets.

Name: Jean-Luc Picard
Key: '''TV Picard''' | '''Movie Picard''' | '''Piloting auxiliary crafts''' | '''Assimilated into the Borg'''
Summary: Jean-Luc Picard, known to the Borg Collective by his designation of Locutus, was a celebrated Starfleet officer, archaeologist and diplomat who served during the latter two thirds of the 24th century. The highlights of his career were centered around assignments as commanding officer of the Federation starships: USS Stargazer, USS Enterprise-D, and the USS Enterprise-E. In these roles, Picard not only witnessed the major turning points of recent galactic history, but also played a key role in them, from making first contact as captain of the Federation's flagship with 27 alien species, including the Ferengi and the Borg.

Name: Kamen Rider Saber
Key: '''Beginning of Story (1-22)''' | '''Middle of Story (23-35)''' | '''Late Story (36-40)''' | '''End of Story (41-47)'''
Summary: https://vsbattles.fandom.com/wiki/File:KRSaber_Brave_Dragon_Sound.mp3

Name: Kha'Zix
Summary: A vicious Void predator, Kha'Zix infiltrated Valoran to devour the land's most promising creatures. With each kill he absorbs his prey's strength, evolving to grow more powerful. Kha'Zix hungers most to conquer and consume Rengar, the one beast he considers his equal.

Name: Kog'Maw
Summary: Belched forth from a rotting Void incursion deep in the wastelands of Icathia, Kog’Maw is an inquisitive yet putrid creature with a caustic, gaping mouth. This particular Void-spawn needs to gnaw and drool on anything within reach to truly understand it. Though not inherently evil, Kog’Maw’s beguiling naiveté is dangerous, as it often precedes a feeding frenzy—not for sustenance, but to satisfy its unending curiosity.

Name: Leonal
Summary: Leonals are lion-like celestials hailing from the plains of Elysium, and belong to the Guardinals, a type of angelic cross of abstract goodness and the animals of nature. As such, Leonal are incredible defenders of the natural world, as well as icons of the armies of Mystra, defending the proper usage of magic throughout the Planes.

Name: Living Laser
Summary: Arthur Parks, better known as The Living Laser is a Marvel character who first appeared at Avengers (1968) issue #34.

Name: Lizardfolk
Summary: Lizardfolk are reptilian humanoids native to the world of Toril that tend to dwell in semi-aquatic environments (such as swamplands and coastlines). An exceedingly practical folk, they do not desire riches or knowledge that don't have use in normal day-to-day survival activities. Their people are hardy, and can adapt to most environments- so despite being dominated culturally by the likes of humans, dwarves, and elves, they rarely hold complaint for the lands leftover for their dominions.

Name: Mao Mao
Summary: Mao Mao (full name Mao Mao Mao) is the primary protagonist and titular character of the Cartoon Network series, Mao Mao: Heroes of Pure Heart. Originally, he and his friend, Badgerclops were but a band of rogue heroes trying to defeat the villainous Sky Pirates led by Orangusnake. Until Mao Mao and Badgerclops crashed into the Ruby Pure Heart: a barrier shielding Pure Heart Valley from the forces of evil. Feeling guilty for his actions, Mao Mao stayed in the village to protect its citizens from dangerous monsters and invaders. Later finding out the Ruby Pure Heart is a mystical artifact wanted by those seeking glory and recruiting a young girl wishing to be a hero like him named Adorabat. Now defender of the valley, he fights to uphold justice and one day become a legend known and beloved by all.

Name: Maokai
Summary: Tier: 8-B | 7-A | High 6-A

Name: Marid
Summary: Marids are aquatic genies hailing from the Elemental Plane of Water. While not evil, they are known to bend wishes to their liking. They are extremely rare on the Prime, more often being seen in the Elemental Plane of Water, inhabiting a vast coral palace in the mightiest reefs of the plane. All Marids declare themselves royalty and lords, though few have the power to enforce such expansive titles. Their ego is their greatest weakness, often lending them to weave legendary tales of their awesome might.

Name: Mind Flayer (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Mind Flayers are horrific, eldritch creatures associated with the dark depths of the D&D settings. They are renowned for being horrendously evil and for their mental capacities. Mind Flayers thrive by devouring the minds of other creatures, generally only interacting with other species at all to eat them or to enslave their kind.

Name: Mira (Toilet in Wonderland)
Summary: Mira is the main protagonist of Toilet in Wonderland. In the beginning of the game, she wakes up in a dream world that was created by her constipation. Her constipation level starts off at 100%, and as she collects laxatives and discovers the game's various magic toilets, that level will drop. If the level is dropped to 0%, the true ending will be unlocked.

Name: MOAB
Summary: The GBU-43/B Massive Ordnance Air Blast (commonly known as the Mother of All Bombs) is a large-yield conventional (non-nuclear) bomb, developed for the United States military by Albert L. Weimorts, Jr. of the Air Force Research Laboratory. At the time of development, it was touted as the most powerful non-nuclear weapon ever designed. The bomb was designed to be delivered by a C-130 Hercules, primarily the MC-130E Combat Talon I or MC-130H Combat Talon II variants.

Name: Modron
Summary: Quote? You desire a quote? The One and the Prime does not give 'quotes'.

Name: Moon Knight (Marvel Comics)
Summary: While on a mission in Sudan, mercenary Marc Spector was left for dead in the desert by Raul Bushman, a ruthless African general, but was afterwards resurrected by the ancient Egyptian moon god known as Khonshu in exchange for being his avatar on Earth. Marc would later return to New York City and become the vigilante known as Moon Knight. Marc Spector possesses multiple personalities, such as the millionaire entrepreneur Steven Grant and cab driver Jake Lockley, and suffers from dissociative identity disorder, which causes great mental stress and instability that has made him an unstable and volatile person.

Name: Mystra (Midnight)
Key: '''Beginning of the Avatar Crisis''' | '''End of the Avatar Crisis''' | '''Avatar''' | '''Greater God'''
Summary: Before she was the God of magic, Mystra was known as the wizard Midnight. Born Ariel Manx, she was the second child of the merchant Theus. A hedonist, Ariel would spend her time with the local bards, sorcerers, fighters, and thieves where she would eventually earn her nickname Midnight due to her late night activities. Eventually she would develop a fascination with magic and left her home in the pursuit of a higher calling.

Name: Natsuko Aki (Re)
Summary: Natsuko Aki is a police inspector in the Re:Cutie Honey continuity. Initially hostile towards Cutie Honey on account of her destructive battles and believing they do more harm, rather than good, she eventually begins to warm up to her, becoming one of her most trusted, devoted, and valuable allies.

Name: Nidalee
Summary: Raised in the deepest jungle, Nidalee is a master tracker who can shapeshift into a ferocious cougar at will. Neither wholly woman nor beast, she viciously defends her territory from any and all trespassers, with carefully placed traps and deft spear throws. She cripples her quarry before pouncing on them in feline form—the lucky few who survive tell tales of a wild woman with razor-sharp instincts, and even sharper claws...

Name: Niffty
Summary: This article contains plot details about an upcoming or recently released episode/chapter/movie/book/game/etc.

Name: Nightmare (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Nightmares are horse-like creatures originating from the Lower Planes, such as the Abyss, the Nine Hells, or Gehenna. They are the standard choice of mount for high-ranking fiends and undead alike, most often searching devil and demon lords, vampires, liches, and other evil-aligned creatures such as the shadar-kai. They are truly wicked beings and are best known for their flaming bodies and vicious tempers.

Name: Norman Osborn
Summary: Norman Osborn is the corrupt founder and head of Oscorp, a multi-billion dollar multinational corporation. After he took the experimental "Goblin Formula" to enhance his intelligence, his already unstable mind fractured further, leading to him becoming the original Green Goblin. In this role, he has been Spider-Man's greatest and most persistent archenemy, responsible for the death of Gwen Stacy. While his primary opponent and obsession is Spider-Man, his goals have branched out further in the past, and, at one time, he was the director of H.A.M.M.E.R., a replacement for S.H.I.E.L.D., and the leader of an Avengers populated by "reformed" supervillains, as the "Iron Patriot".

Name: Orangusnake
Summary: "Lord" Orangusnake is one of the primary antagonists of the Cartoon Network series, Mao Mao: Heroes of Pure Heart. Underhanded and fierce all in one, he leads the treacherous Sky Pirates with the goal of seizing the legendary Ruby Pure Heart and then conquering the world. However he wasn’t always so powerful; originally being two lone criminals. A snake named Coby and an orangutan named Tanner who merged to become much more powerful and intimidating than they ever would be alone. Combined, they serve as the most dangerous and recurring threat to Pure Heart Valley and its sheriffs. Never backing down despite their numerous losses, determined to make Mao Mao truly fear them.

Name: Punisher (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Lt. Frank Castle returned home from duty only to see his wife and children murdered in front of him in cold blood by the Mafia. Unable to find justice by any fair means for them, Castle vowed to spend the rest of his life avenging them. Now equipped with state-of-the-art weapons, decades of combat experience, guerrilla and urban warfare techniques, as well as detective-like skills, he wages a one-man war against crime as the Punisher, a murderous vigilante that takes no prisoners, and comes at odds with both heroes and villains for his methods.

Name: Purple Worm
Summary: A powerful beast, the Purple Worm is a massive worm which tunnels in the ground in constant search of food, the tunnels it leaves behind are often used by other underground races as living places. In combat a Purple Worm simply tries to sting, bite and swallow its prey until it's dead.

Name: Rakshasa (Dungeons and Dragons)
Key: '''Rakshasa''' | '''Greater Rakshasa''' | '''Ak'chazar''' | '''Naztharune''' | '''Dread Knight''' | '''Lord of Dust''' | '''Zakya''' | '''Half-Dragon Rakshasa''' | '''Naityan Rakshasa''' | '''Overlord'''
Summary: Rakshasa are fiendish creatures born from the Lower Planes with the appearance of humanoid tigers of proud stature, distinguishable from similar creatures such as Weretigers by their hands, which can bend both backwards and forwards. Extravagant and conniving by nature, Rakshasa plague all the Planes with their manipulations, constantly enacting plots to achieve greater power. They serve countless masters- their own Rajahs, demon lords[1], yugoloths, night hags, and even the mightiest of devils. As manipulators and masterminds, the Rakshasa ply their trade from their luxuriously decorated palaces, subtly tipping the scales in planar and political conflicts as it suited their wants.

Name: Ras Nsi
Summary: Ras Nsi was once a Chosen of Ubtao, a Primordial planar power residing in Chult. Some time long ago, however, he cast off his oaths and his power, and became an evil warlord, raising the dead to be his armies. When he did so, he lost control of his necromantic hordes, and in his defeat sought out the Yuan-Ti of Omu to take control.

Name: Rath Modar
Summary: Rath Modar is a Red Wizard of Thay and the primary conspirator against the lich Szass Tam in the campaign to retake Thay. During the crisis concerning the Cult of the Dragons, Rath offered his wizards' might to assist the cult in their goal of summoning Tiamat from the Nine Hells. It was his silent hope that Tiamat would, when she saw how useful he had been, offer to him an army of dragons to wipe out Szass Tam once and for all.

Name: Rek'Sai
Summary: The largest and fiercest of her species, Rek'Sai is a merciless predator that tunnels through the earth to ambush and devour her prey. Her insatiable hunger has laid waste to entire regions of the once-great Shuriman empire. Merchants, traders and armed caravans will go hundreds of miles out of their way to avoid these vast areas, though cunning bandits have been known to lure the unwary into her killing grounds. Once Rek'Sai detects you, your fate is sealed. There is no hope of escape; she is death from below the sand.

Name: Remorhaz
Summary: Native to frozen lands, the Remorhaz spends all its days hunting prey. They are a millipede like creature that emits incredible heat from its body, using it burrow through ice without any issue.

Name: Rengar
Summary: Rengar is a ferocious vastayan trophy hunter who lives for the thrill of tracking down and killing dangerous creatures. He scours the world for the most fearsome beasts he can find, especially seeking any trace of Kha'Zix, the void creature who scratched out his eye. Rengar stalks his prey neither for food nor glory, but for the sheer beauty of the pursuit.

Name: Retriever
Summary: Retrievers are the "gopher" units of any demonic fiefdom. Whenever a powerful lord or commander desires to search out lost artifacts, runaway slaves, or unruly underlings, the Retriever is sent out to find them and return them through any means possible. Most scholars can agree that the Retriever is built to mimic the structural design of the Bebilith, though the reason is unknown. Since they are constructs that are easily accessible to most demonic leaders, the Retrievers are also regularly entrusted with tasks that cannot be given to the demon's kin, for their ugly kind are not reliable.

Name: Rezmir the Black
Summary: Rezmir is a black half-dragon warrior placed in charge of a regional sect of the Cult of the Dragon, an organization dedicated to furthering Tiamat's goals across the plains. Around the time of Rezmir's leadership, the cult grew greatly in power and began to enact a plan to bring living dragons to great power, and eventually summon the Dragon Queen herself.

Name: Roc
Summary: A massive bird, the Roc is the supreme ruler of the skies in the mountains. They only go against large targets such as elephants, with the Roc being able to lift them with one leg. Sometimes Cloud and Storm Giants tame Rocs and use them as a deadly asset.

Name: Roper
Summary: The larva form, also known as a Piercer is an ambush predator in underground places that uses it camouflage in order to let itself drop upon prey whenever it senses someone below it. The adult form, also known as a Roper meanwhile is a far more active hunter, which while still using stealth, also employs tentacles it tosses at enemies in order to pull them to its maw.

Name: Shruikan
Summary: Shruikan was a black male Dragon, forcibly bonded to Galbatorix. He was the only dragon other than Glaedr to survive the Fall of the Dragon Riders to modern times. Galbatorix used Magic to artificially speed up Shruikan's growth, making him gigantic in size.

Name: Sister Dagger (Marvel Comics)
Summary: One of the many daughters of the sorcerer and crimelord Zheng Zu, Zheng Esme was raised in the House of the Deadly Dagger outside of Paris, France, eventually becoming its Champion, Sister Dagger. When Sister Hammer named herself as the new Supreme Commander of the Five Weapons Society over its rightful successor, Shang-Chi, Sister Dagger and Brother Sabre approached their half-brother to usurp Hammer. Shang-Chi reluctantly joined them to free his remaining family from his father's cult.

Name: Spider-Man (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Peter Benjamin Parker, more well-known as Spider-Man, was once just a nerdy teenager in High School. But after he was bitten by a radioactive spider at a science exhibition, he gained the proportionate strength, speed, and agility of a spider alongside a special precognitive ability known as the "Spider Sense" to warn him of incoming danger. However, after using his powers to in a wrestling match to earn money yet not prevent a burglary going on backstage that he had witnessed first-hand, he later returned home to find out that his Uncle Ben was murdered by someone who broke into their house.

Name: Stone Giant
Key: '''Regular''' | '''Elder''' | '''Dreamwalker''' | '''Cairwight''' | '''Stalker of Baphomet''' | '''Evil Earth''' | '''Runecarver''' | '''Earth Titan''' | '''Rockspeaker''' | '''Scion of Skoraeus'''
Summary: One of the main giant races, the Stone Giant is a mighty foe for anyone to face. They are hulking, gray-skinned humanoid-looking creatures that stand 18 feet tall. They can live up to 800 years, and while they're not the smartest of the Giant kin, they are usually far smarter than the likes of Hill Giants.

Name: Stone Golem (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: The Stone Golem is the strongest of the common golems, often also being the prettiest looking due to being often assigned to guard museums.

Name: Susztam Mar-Shinn
Summary: Susztam is the Head Student of the Inverted Tower, a Drow outpost of arcane learning located in Szith Mercane. As the Head Student, he maintains the greatest control over his magic, and one day hopes to usurp his master in becoming the position of his master- until then, he spends his days in the Inverted Tower, training and learning constantly. He is particularly known to be a master of illusory spells and makes use of them frequently[1]. The position of head student is one envied by his peers, and thus Susztam spends his days preparing for their inevitable betrayal[2]. During the takeover of Szith Mercane, Susztam has entered the service of Dorina T'sarran, occasionally acting as a strike-team killer on her behalf[3].

Name: The Recruit (Transformers)
Summary: The Recruit is a rookie who arrived on Earth during the to help either the Autobots or the Decepticons to destroy the opposing force on earth. Unlike his predecessor, he can scan various weapons & power-ups that can help him during his missions.

Name: Tornado
Summary: A tornado is a violently rotating column of air, in contact with the ground, either pendant from a cumuliform cloud or underneath a cumuliform cloud, and often (but not always) visible as a funnel cloud. Tornadoes come in many shapes and sizes, but they are typically in the form of a visible condensation funnel originating from the base of a huge storm cloud, whose narrow end touches the earth and is often encircled by a basal cloud of debris and dust. Most tornadoes have wind speeds less than 110 miles per hour (180 km/h), are about 250 feet (80 m) across, and travel a few miles (several kilometers) before dissipating. The most extreme tornadoes can attain wind speeds of more than 300 miles per hour (480 km/h), are more than two miles (3 km) in diameter, and stay on the ground for dozens of miles (more than 100 km).

Name: Trienath Salazar
Summary: Trienath Salazar is a veteran Hellbreaker, a group of thieves adept at intruding into the depths of Baator and taking the diabolical treasure from within. Trienath is fleeing from the Pit Fiend Zaebos, a member of the Dark Eight of Avernus, and offers to help player characters if she finds them to be righteous.

Name: Umber Hulk
Key: '''Umber Hulk''' | '''Truly Horrid Umber Hulk''' | '''Vodyanoi''' | '''Shadow Hulk''' | '''Umber Ravager''' | '''Abyssal Hulk''' | '''Astral Hulk'''
Summary: Umber Hulks are ancient mutant creatures born countless eons ago, possibly before the onset of the Dawn War[1]. Hulking bug-eyed monstrosities, the Umber Hulks lurk in the Underdark, tunneling from cavern to cavern in search of food (and little else), often causing wars and conflicts over territory as they move. They are feared on a nearly mythological level to some due to their peculiar ability to incapacitate hostiles with a glance- and leave survivors with nary a memory of what occurred.

Name: Vel'Koz
Summary: Tier: 8-B | 7-A | High 6-C

Name: Velasta and Velina T'sarran
Summary: Velasta and Velina T'sarran are a pair of Drow identical twins, nieces of Irae T'sarran who server under her daughter, Dorina, in Szith Mercane. Their duties there vary from humdrum to violent, but primarily include raiding on the surface and serving in the elite Hunter-Killer team alongside Susztam Mar-Shinn and Zedarr T'sarran[1]. While they are considered somewhat important to Irae's plans, if slain they are not outright given the time or resources for resurrection- instead they rise as revenants created by Irae.

Name: Venom Ooze
Summary: Theorised to be off shoots of ochre jellies this ooze is atypical in that it doesn't remain mostly in one spot and instead seeks out prey actively, which it's able to capture with its great strength and potent poison. This ooze is most commonly found in the Underdark alone but have been known to be used by evil individuals or simply migrated to another environment due to their incredible resistance to the elements.

Name: Verdant Prince
Summary: Verdant Princes are powerful fey that roam the Prime Material, offering pacts with adventurers or even entire families. While often the pacts seem benign in nature (generally, the Prince won't even profit from the pact for many generations), each is in fact a malign curse on the pact-bearer, where when the Prince's plans come to fruition, that individual's descendants may well pay the full price of their ancestor's impudence.

Name: Viserion
Summary: Viserion is one of the dragons born in the Dothraki Sea, along with Drogon and Rhaegal. He is named after Daenerys Targaryen's brother, Viserys Targaryen. He is distinguishable by his cream and gold colored scales, and red-orange wings. Eventually, after being killed, became a Wight and was enslaved by the Night King.

Name: Vitreous Drinker
Summary: Vitreous Drinkers are undead servants of Vecna, known to wander the lands stealing their victims' eyesight. To do this, they collect certain arcane items to surprise and ambush targets, and uses its skills to, after the attack, see through their victims' eyes. As worshippers of the God of Secrets, they often target great sages, spies, and magi to gain their information.

Name: W54 warhead
Summary: Tier: High 8-C to 8-B | High 8-C to 8-A | 8-A | 8-A

Name: War Machine (Marvel Comics)
Summary: War Machine (James Rupert "Rhodey" Rhodes) is a fictional character, a superhero appearing in comic books set in the Marvel Comics universe.

Name: War Machine Armor Model 1
Summary: The Iron Man Armor Model 11 was created by Tony Stark, who added immense weapon artillery into the suit. He then later modified and gave the armor to Rhodey, who would fight in this armor as War Machine.

Name: War Machine Armor Model 2
Summary: After Parnell Jacobs found the War Machine Model 1, he brought it to Stuart Clarke, who in turn brought it to Sunset Bain, who rebuilt the armor with her own technology.

Name: Water Weird
Summary: Made from water, the Water Weird is one of the possible Elemental Weirds. In their younger form they appear like a water serpent, shooting cold water at enemies and using their physiology to drown people who come close to them. Their adult self meanwhile is a powerful caster, being able to use various healing and water spells alongside regular Sorcerer spells.

Name: Wheep
Summary: An eyeless pathetic creature, the Wheep is a servant of other more powerful creatures which is often used as a bodyguard. It constantly emits a black vile from its eyes which makes tracking it down rather easy, although if they choose to, a Wheep is more than capable of using stealth to gain the edge in combat.

Name: White Rabbit (Marvel Comics)
Summary: White Rabbit: We don't need them! We're the Terrible Two! We're evil personified! The vilest villains on the face of the-- Walrus: They hung up on you, didn't they? White Rabbit: Uh-huh. After they were done laughing.

Name: Wights
Summary: A Wight is a reanimated corpse, either human or animal, raised from death by the Night King or the White Walkers with the use of necromancy. Wights were often referred to collectively as the Army of the Dead. Anyone who falls against the White Walkers must be burned, or else the dead will rise again as their slaves. Fear of their own dead becoming wights leads the free folk to burn them.

Name: Yagnoloth
Summary: Yagnoloths are the minor lords of the yugoloth armies, controlling small swathes of the Lower Middle planes as command posts in the Blood War. They serve as basic negotiators for the yugoloth mercenary forces, and tend to bring in contracts for arcanaloths. They are most known for two distinctive traits- firstly, the physical trait of a single massively swelled arm, and secondly, the manipulative trait of always including a loophole in their contracts that voids the entire contract should the situation call for it.

Name: Yorick Mori
Summary: The last survivor of a long-forgotten religious order, Yorick is both blessed and cursed with power over the dead. Trapped on the Shadow Isles, his only companions are the rotting corpses and shrieking spirits that he gathers to him. Yorick's monstrous actions belie his noble purpose: to free his home from the curse of the Ruination.

Name: Zephiel (Fire Emblem)
Summary: Zephiel (ゼフィール Zefīru, Zefhyr in the Japanese versions) is the main antagonist of Fire Emblem: The Binding Blade and a minor non-playable character in its prequel, Fire Emblem: The Blazing Blade.

Name: A-10 Thunderbolt II
Summary: The A-10 Thunderbolt II is a close-air support and forward air control aircraft designed to tank hits from high-explosive and armor piercing rounds up to at least 23 mm. It was designed by the company known as Fairchild Republic. It is primarily used by the US military.

Name: Aboleth
Summary: Aboleths are ancient, primordial entities that have existed since the creation of the multiverse, supposedly being spontaneously created when the empty void of reality was touched by an alien entity in the Far Realm, allowing the Aboleths to bleed into the multiverse. They formed an empire throughout the void through sheer psionic might, being the gods before gods came to be- though the dawn of these creatures, the gods as we know them, caused the Abolethic Sovereignity to crumble.

Name: Abomination (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Emil Blonsky was a special-ops commando with the British Royal Marines on loan to General Thaddeus Ross in his efforts to capture Bruce Banner better known as Hulk. Blonsky was injected with two dosages of a variant original Super Soldier Serum and later was injected with Bruce Banner's blood causing him to transform into the Hulk-sized Abomination. The Abomination proceeded to go on a rampage in Harlem until he was defeated by Hulk and captured by the United States Armed Forces.

Name: Aerosaur
Summary: One of the All-Father's ancient creations, the Aerosaur is a hulking flier, with size on par with ancient dragons. Its wingspan reaches 200 feet, with lightning like pattern across its body, with it giving its wing flaps additional thunderous power.

Name: Agatha Harkness (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Agatha Harkness is a witch who was a member of the Salem Witch Coven, and daughter to its leader, Evanora Harkness. After being put on trial for execution in 1693 for practicing dark magic and betraying her coven, Agatha killed her clan and her mother through the use of her dark magic, after they attempted to execute her for her crimes. Agatha absorbed their magic in the process and took the brooch off of her mother's rotten corpse before flying off. Hundreds of years later in the modern day, Agatha resurfaced and took on the name 'Agnes' and entered the town of Westview, New Jersey to investigate the odd Pocket Reality created by Wanda Maximoff, encasing the town. Agatha then meets Wanda herself and observes her under the suspicion that Wanda may be the Scarlet Witch, a powerful mythical being referenced in the Darkhold, desiring to take her chaotic powers for herself.

Name: Ancient One (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: The Ancient One was the Sorcerer Supreme and leader of the Masters of the Mystical Arts. She taught Kaecilius, Karl Mordo, Wong, and many others in the ways of sorcery. Her unusually long life is fuelled by her energy use from the Dark Dimension, a technique she prohibits others from doing. When Kaecilius challenged the Ancient One's ways and stole a spell from the forbidden Book of Cagliostro, the Ancient One was determined to prevent Kaecilius from summoning Dormammu to the Earth.

Name: Arataki Itto
Summary: Arataki Itto is a playable Geo character in Genshin Impact. A loud and proud descendant of the crimson oni, Itto is also the leader and founder of the Arataki Gang. While not a villain, his reputation as a delinquent in Inazuma City leaves something to be desired.

Name: Archangel (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Warren Worthington III was a mutant member of the X-Men, named Angel, who was born with a pair of wings until he was one day captured by En Sabah Nur. Apocalypse brainwashed Warren and enhanced his body with modifications, turning him into his "Horseman of Death" Archangel.

Name: Archelon Ischyras
Summary: A prehistoric aquatic reptile, the Archelon Ischyras is a giant sea turtle. They often feed on carrion and shellfish but they will hunt other creatures, even venturing above land to snack on beach dwellers.

Name: Athach
Summary: Athachs are a bizarre alteration on the typical giant form, a dull-witted, lumbering, clumsy brand of enormous humanoid whose most noticeable trait was the additional arm centered on their torso. Despite their giant-like appearance, they hated hill giants and their lesser, and outright feared and fled from higher tiers of giants.

Name: Aurora (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Aurora, the twin sister of Northstar, was a founding member of Alpha Flight. She also suffers from dissociative identity disorder, which often causes her to be caught in precarious situations.

Name: Avengers (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Iron Man: How were you guys planning on beating that? Captain America: Together. Iron Man: We'll lose. Captain America: Then we'll do that together, too.

Name: Avoral
Summary: Avorals are bird-like (specifically bearing a resemblance to eagles) guardinals, a species of celestial that watched over the plane of Elysium and the House of Nature. As a species, the avorals shared a collective wanderlust- a tendency to abandon their celestial duties and walk through the Planes, experiencing all nature could display. While Avorals largely served their leader, Sathia the Sky Duchess, much like all guardinals they were often found in the service of Mystra and her champions (such as Elminster).

Name: Azazel (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Azazel claimed he was one of the oldest mutants, part of a group of demonic-looking mutants called the Neyaphem. He even claimed that he once battled Mephisto and others for the title of "Satan". The Neyaphem were eventually banished to the Brimstone Dimension by another group of mutants with angelic appearances, the Cheyarafim.

Name: Azrael (Jean-Paul Valley)
Summary: Jean-Paul Valley, better known as Azrael, is a vigilante who formerly operated out of Gotham City. Most of his extraordinary abilities come from severe amounts of subconscious training and conditioning he was put through during his youth, unaware that he was being controlled by a 500-year-old devout religious sect called the Order of St Dumas. Named after the Angle Of Death, Jean-Paul Valley is actually descended from a long line of crimefighters using the Azrael suit and name. As Azrael, his main nemesis was Carleton Lehah an evil man of wealth who believed himself to be serving the demon Biis, the Order of St. Dumas' sworn enemy.

Name: Azumarill
Summary: Tier: 8-C, higher with Huge Power | At most Low 7-B, higher with Huge Power | At least High 7-A, 6-C with Huge Power

Name: B-1 Lancer
Summary: The Rockwell (Now part of Boeing) B-1 Lancer is a four engine, supersonic variable sweep swing strategic bomber developed in the 1960s originally to replace the aging B-52 Stratofortress. The bomber's original design has evolved into the current B-1B Lancer, a low-level penetration bomber with a long range while retaining supersonic capability.

Name: B-17 Flying Fortress
Summary: The B-17 Flying Fortress is a four engine heavy bomber designed by Boeing, primarily employed by the US Army Air Corps in the European theatre as a strategic bomber against German targets, but also saw service albeit in lesser quantities against the Japanese in the Pacific Theatre. The long range, durability, heavy defensive armament, and speed of the aircraft lent it it's reputation as a strategic bomber. Over 10,000 were built over the course of World War II.

Name: B-2 Spirit
Summary: The B-2 Spirit is a 2-seat stealth bomber developed by Northrop-Grumman. It is a heavy penetration strategic bomber sporting low observable stealth technology for piercing into high density air defenses. It is capable of carrying both conventional and nuclear payloads. There are currently 21 built.

Name: B-52 Stratofortress
Summary: The B-52 Stratofortress is a strategic bomber developed by Boeing. It is a long range jet powered aircraft and has been operated by the USAF since the 1950s and still continues to serve the USAF to this day with continuing upgrades and maintenance. The B-52 made its first flight on April 1952. It was also made to replace the earlier Convair B-36 peacemaker, especially in the role of carrying nuclear weapons for Cold War-era deterrence missions.

Name: Baltimore-class Heavy Cruiser
Summary: The Baltimore-class Heavy Cruiser was a large class of heavy cruisers in the United States Navy commissioned during or shortly after World War II. Fourteen Baltimores were completed, more than any other class of heavy cruiser, along with three ships of the Oregon City-class sub-class. Fast and heavily armed, the Baltimore cruisers were mainly used in World War II to protect the fast aircraft carriers in battle groups from air attack. Additionally, their 8"/55 (203mm) main guns and secondary 5"/38 (127mm) guns were regularly used to bombard land targets in support of amphibious landings. After the war, only six Baltimores and two Oregon City-class ships remained in service, while the rest were moved to the reserve fleet.

Name: Bane (Post-Crisis)
Summary: This man was born in the prison of Peña Duro, where he would have to serve a life sentence in the place of his father. He grew up in the prison, and killing one of his fellow prisoners, the guards bestowed a name upon him: Bane. The prison guards locked Bane in a pit for ten years as penance, expecting him to die, but he survived and became a legend to the other inmates. Bane trained his mind and his body and was eventually chosen as a test subject for a drug called Venom. Bane was the only subject who survived the test, and he was subsequently given surgery so the drug could be injected directly into his brain. After faking his own death to escape Peña Duro, Bane returned to free the inmates, kill the warden and steal a helicopter so he could travel to Gotham City, home of the man that Bane wanted to destroy: the Batman.

Name: Bane (Post-Flashpoint)
Summary: Bane is an international super-criminal who used his intellect and immense strength, enhanced by a drug called Venom, in his pursuit for power. He once set his sights on Gotham City, making him an enemy of Batman.

Name: Batman (Millerverse)
Summary: It's a SHAME to expose one of my SAFE HOUSES. Now it'll be USELESS. But I've got DOZENS around town, and this one's RENT wouldn't amount to a VALET TIP. Hell. It'll be worth TEN TIMES the rent just to get a chance to knock the SNOT out of GREEN LANTERN. This guy really GRINDS MY GEARS. Here he's got a POWER RING that can do ANYTHING he can IMAGINE-- but that's his whole PROBLEM. He's got the IMAGINATION of a goddamn POTATO. He makes giant green FISHING POLES and MOUSETRAPS when he could, well... ...Put that ring on MY finger and just as a WARM-UP I'd send a few TIDAL WAVES in just the right DIRECTIONS. Knock out a few ENEMY FLEETS. Then get started on bringing some REAL firepower to a nasty GROUND WAR or two. Then maybe I'd spank SUPERMAN'S butt back to what's left of KRYPTON. Just for LAUGHS. Thing is, old Hal (Hal Jordan, that's his real name-- the moron can't keep any secrets from ME), old Hal, he can't even make himself a green DANDELION with that RING of his if what he's up against is YELLOW. Dumbest WEAKNESS I ever HEARD of...

Name: Batman (Post-Flashpoint)
Summary: Batman is a fictional superhero appearing in American comic books published by DC Comics. The character was created by artist Bob Kane and writer Bill Fsuinger, and first appeared in Detective Comics #27 (May 1939). Originally named "the Bat-Man", the character is also referred to by such epithets as the "Caped Crusader," the "Dark Knight," and the "World's Greatest Detective".

Name: Beast (Marvel Comics)
Summary: One of the founding X-Men, Dr. Hank McCoy is a mutant possessing animal-like strength and agility. Despite being covered in blue fur and resembling a ferocious beast he possesses an astounding intellect and superb wit. Beast is currently helping the Jean Grey School run, while also serving as an Avenger.

Name: Bebilith
Summary: Bebiliths are enormous, powerful demons known for eating anything- including other demons- alive. They constantly search for prey out in the ravaged terrains of the Abyss, and are generally considered more of an animal than a true demon. However, that is not to say they are unintelligent- they comprehend language fine, they merely refrain from using it. Why converse with your prey, after all?

Name: Beedrill
Summary: Beedrill is a Poison/Bug, wasp based Pokémon introduced in the first generation. It is noted to be incredibly territorial and poisonous. It evolves from Weedle into Kakuna at level 7, and then from Kakuna into Beedrill at level 10.

Name: Behir
Summary: Behirs are dragon-like creatures of electric origin that despise their brethren, to the point of driving them out of their territories if possible and, if not, leaving the area. They were created by Storm Dragons as weapons in a great war against the dragons, though nowadays are often kept as pets of powerful spellcasters and serve as signs of good omens for certain religions, notably in Chult.

Name: Bishop (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Lucas Bishop is a mutant from the 22nd century that traveled into the past, becoming a member of the X-Men, and later, the Uncanny X-Force. He has the power to channel kinetic energy, releasing it generally through beams of energy.

Name: Black Knight (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Dane Whitman is a fictional superhero appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. He is the company's third character to bear the name Black Knight. Created by writer Roy Thomas and artist John Buscema, he first appeared in The Avengers #47 (December 1967)

Name: Black Panther (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: T'Challa, also known by the moniker of Black Panther, is the protector of the nation of Wakanda. Following the untimely death of his father T'Chaka, he inherited his father's position as king. In his rush to avenge his father, he became involved in the internal conflict among the Avengers, siding with Iron Man. However, upon seeing how vengeance drove Helmut Zemo's actions and subsequently Iron Man's as well, he saw the error of his judgement and became an ally to Captain America.

Name: Black Panther (Marvel Comics)
Summary: The Black Panther (T'Challa) is a fictional character appearing in publications by Marvel Comics. Created by writer-editor Stan Lee and penciller-co-plotter Jack Kirby, he first appeared in Fantastic Four #52 (July 1966).

Name: Blaspheme
Summary: Blasphemes are specially-crafted undead as perfect guardians for power-hungry wizards. They are still wandering in ancient cities while their masters lay dead. The secret to creating these creatures has been lost, leaving the few left to wander their old master's territories.

Name: Blazing Skull (Post-Golden Age)
Summary: Foreign correspondent and pacifist reporter Mark Todd was forced to take refuge in a cave during an artillery bombardment by the Japanese. There he met the Skull Men, a strange race with burning skulls for heads, who chose him to be the champion of freedom, and began his training which granted him abilities such as invulnerability to fire. Once his training was completed, he returned home and, motivated by the horrors of Nazism, he fought against tyranny across Europe, as the World War 2 icon, Blazing Skull

Name: Bleakborn
Summary: Bleakborn are undead risen from souls slain by bitter coldness. As such, they crave the warmth of life, absorbing heat to sustain themselves in the same way that normal zombies crave flesh. They are also known as moil zombies, referring to the city they hail from.

Name: Blood Amniote
Summary: Blood Amniotes are massive creatures with forms made of the blood of past victims. It craves blood, seeking to pierce the flesh of living creatures to draw it out. While the creature itself is essentially mindless, it does bear the vestiges of past victims that form faces on the outside of its skin.

Name: Bloodfire Ooze
Summary: Created from a dark ritual, a Bloodfire Ooze is an ooze that's made from people's blood with a bit of a demon added in. They are mindless beasts that seek out blood to absorb and use their fire abilities in battle, some Bloodfire Oozes are even more horrid when made by an extraplaner for they add a pseudonatural creature template which makes the Bloodfire a Blight Bloodfire

Name: Bloodhound LSR
Summary: The Bloodhound Land Speed Record is a British supersonic land vehicle. Its goal is to match or exceed 1,000 miles per hour (1,609 km/h), achieving a new world land speed record. The pencil-shaped car, powered by a jet engine and a rocket engine, is designed to reach 1,050 miles per hour (1,690 km/h).

Name: Bone Devil
Summary: Osyluths, or Bone Devils as they are more commonly known as, are powerful (if petty) taskmasters of hell, powerful warriors constantly seeking promotion. The promotion to their next form was lethal, including immense torture, including the loss of all limbs and flaying of the skin.

Name: Booster Gold (Post-Crisis)
Summary: In the 25th century, Michael Jon Carter was a great quarterback football player in Gotham University until his father, who had vanished for most of his life (and previously run his family broke due to his gambling addiction) reappeared and convinced him to intentionally throw games for money. Expelled and disgraced upon discovery of this, Michael later worked at a space museum containing artifacts from the 20th century. This inspired him to steal some of the artifacts, time travel to the 20th century and become the superhero Booster Gold.

Name: Bowser's Brother
Summary: Bowser's Brother[1], is a member of Bowser's family. He shows up only in Super Mario Bros.: The Lost Levels and then never again, only being referenced here and there.

Name: Bradley Fighting Vehicle
Summary: The Bradley Fighting Vehicle (BFV) is a fighting vehicle platform of the United States manufactured by BAE Systems Land & Armaments, formerly United Defense. It was named after U.S. General Omar Bradley.

Name: Brain Golem (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Made entirely from brains the Brain Golem is a horrid creation from the Illithid which is meant to guard their cities and the Elder Brain. This golems are smarter then your average golem although still below humans and possess the ability to create a Mind Blast like their masters, combine that with their impressive physical prowess and they make for deadly opponents.

Name: Brass Golem
Summary: Brass Golems are patient constructs built for one purpose stated at the time of its creation. If that goal becomes unattainable (for example, the location it was protecting becomes destroyed), the magic becomes inert and the golem "dies". While they can feasibly be of any shape, they tend to take the form of minotaurs.

Name: Breachgnome
Summary: Specialized in fighting within cramped spaces, a well-positioned Breachgnome can hold off superior enemy forces for a long duration. They are trained to fight alone, although sometimes they work in small units that coordinate to block off several paths at once. They are seldom seen outside Gnome communities, though when are found outside they are often looking for Gnomes to help.

Name: Bunny (Tiger & Bunny)
Summary: Barnaby Brooks Jr. (バーナビー・ブルックスJr.) is one of the two main characters of Tiger & Bunny. Barnaby Jr. is a rookie hero who does not conceal his secret identity and the newest addition to Hero TV. Partnered with and possessing the same power as Wild Tiger, he relies more on strategy than force. He is liked by many people as he is seen as cool and handsome. He is currently the top-notch hero, with the famous title, "King of Heroes." He has the Hundred Power, the power to increase his physical capabilities (strength, speed, endurance, jumping ability, etc.) like Wild Tiger. He is rather more serious than his partner and believes in satisfying his sponsors than actually saving people. He is very strategical and does not rely on sheer force. His parents were murdered and was adopted by Albert Maverick who became his surrogate uncle. He vows to avenge his parents but he has unclear memories of who was the murderer of his parents.

Name: Bushmaster (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: John McIver, also known as Bushmaster, is the charismatic enhanced individual who had previously witnessed his family being murdered by Mama Mabel as he vowed revenge on the Stokes family. With a mission of vengeance, Bushmaster soon arrived in Harlem to kill Black Mariah, the last member of the Stokes family, only to be challenged by Luke Cage who stood in the way of Bushmaster's revenge mission. Bushmaster's continued attempts to kill Dillard resulted in him becoming mortally wounded, as he sought Tilda Johnson's aid for his recovery. However, Dillard took the opportunity to massacre the remaining members of Bushmaster's family, forcing him to make an uneasy alliance with Cage to stop Dillard's rampage before more innocent people got killed. Eventually however, Bushmaster was forced to return to Jamaica to recover from his near fatal wounds, having failed to kill Dillard himself. (Marvel Cinematic Universe Wiki)

Name: Caitlyn (Arcane)
Summary: Caitlyn Kiramman is a scion of the Kiramman Clan, one of the ruling houses of Piltover. Eager to see the world for herself and disdainful of the traditional elitist lifestyle that her parents had raised her in, Caitlyn joined the Enforcers as a young woman to make a name for herself. When Marcus, the Sheriff of the Enforcers, and her parents-for very different reasons-started blocking her efforts to further investigate an undercity conspiracy, Caitlyn set off on her own to find answers, only to get much more than she bargained for.

Name: Captain America (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Abraham Erskine: Do you want to kill Nazis? Captain America: I don't want to kill anyone, but I don't like bullies; I don't care where they're from.

Name: Captain America (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Born to poor Irish immigrants in the 1920s, Steven Grant Rogers always felt a strong sense of duty to his country and a desire to defend the weak and helpless from those that would prey on them. Unfortunately for him, his impoverished upbringing left him a scrawny and weak youth at the advent of the second World War and was denied enlistment in the U.S. Army.

Name: Captain America (William Burnside)
Summary: Growing up idolizing Captain America, William Burnside got all he ever wanted when he found the Super Serum Formula during the Korean War. Convincing the government to inject it into him, he underwent plastic surgery to make himself a perfect replica of Steve Rogers, and promoted McCarthyist ideologies as the Captain America of the 1950s.

Name: Captain Boomerang Jr. (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Owen Mercer also known as Captain Boomerang Jr. is the son of George Harkness, the original Captain Boomerang and his idol, taking up his mantle after a mission to assassinate the father of Tim Drake went south. He decides to choose to become a different man, to change the outlook of the legacy his father left behind, walking the thin line between hero and villain.

Name: Captain Carter (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Doctor Strange Supreme: You changed your outfit, pretty cool. It’s a good look on you, but you might remember I defeated that armor once before? Captain Carter: Once before I wasn’t in it!

Name: Captain Cold (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Once a jovial, well-respected gentleman thief of a bygone age, Leonard Snart, better known as Captain Cold let his heart grow colder and bitter after the world kept grinding him down and spitting in his face. After many failed heists and the increasing violence of superheroes, Snart became the very thing he hated; a true-blue supervillain, though he never quite lost his core morals of only killing when necessary, or for vengeance. Despite his demeanor and image, Snart was among the most warm-hearted villains on the street, showing compassion for those in need, and truly loved his friends and sister, though rarely let them know it.

Name: Captain Marvel (Mar-Vell)
Summary: Captain Mar-Vell was a member of the Kree, the alien humanoid warrior race which has forged an empire throughout the galaxy known as the Large Magellanic Cloud. More specifically, he was one of the so-called "Pink Kree." This Kree race has the same color skin as Caucasian Earth humans, to whom those Kree who belong to it are more biologically similar than blue Kree are. As such he was chosen to act as a spy in his mission to conquer Earth, taking on the identity of the deceased Dr. Walter Lawson, however Earth and its denizens changed his views as he left the Kree Empire to be one of the Earth's greatest defenders, the original Captain Marvel

Name: Captain Ultra (Marvel Comics)
Summary: When an elderly psychologist couldn't afford to pay plumber Griffin Gogol, he offered to cure Gogol's smoking habit via hypnosis. However, as Gogol later learned, the psychologist was an extraterrestrial, and the hypnosis unlocked Gogol's innate superhuman potential. Donning a staggeringly gaudy costume, Gogol became the superhero Captain Ultra, a part-time hero, part-time stand-up comedian with a phobia of fire.

Name: Carrie Cutter (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Carrie Cutter, also known as Cupid is a former special force operative, specifically working under the COBALT group. After letting multiple kids die on one of her missions she broke down mentally, leading to COBALT to experiment on her with a new drug to try and better her mental condition. Said drug gave her amnesia, and made her become an obsessive lunatic seeking out love at all cost. After Green Arrow fatally shoots a man she poisoned, mistakenly thinking he was beating her, he becomes her new obsession.

Name: Cassandra Nova (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Johnny Storm: And I’ll tell you who ‘her’ is. Cassandra Nova, a megalomaniacal psychotic asshole, a finger-lickin’ dead-inside pixie slab of third rate dime-store nut-milk, and I’ll tell you what she can do. Deadpool: I’m listening. Johnny Storm: She can lick my goddamn cinnamon ring clean and kick rocks all the way to bald hell. In fact, I don’t give a shit if she removes all my skin and pops me like some nightmarish blood balloon. If the last thing I do in this godforsaken cum gutter existence is light that fuck box on fire, I still won’t die happy.

Name: Caterpie
Summary: Butterfree is a dual-type Bug/Flying fully evolved Pokémon based on a butterfly. It evolves from Metapod at level 10, who evolves from Caterpie at level 7. It is also one of few pokemon capable of Gigantamaxing.

Name: Centaur (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Centaurs are a species of half-horse half-humanoid creatures that often wander the planes in tribal communities. Typically Centaurs will avoid conflicts though are known to fight fiercely and to the death if pressed. It is the nature of centaurs to make enormous treks across entire continents, and might take decades to return. Often a conflict will start due to settlements appearing in their nomadic pathways.

Name: Chahir
Summary: Chahir is a vampire sorcerer buried in the Dordrien Crypts of the Underdark. There, he wallows in his tomb, occasionally slaying creatures who would interfere with his dormancy. He does little else due to the death of his wife in Daggerdale, where she was destroyed- her sarcophagus, a great stone thing bearing her likeness sitting opposite to his, now houses two vampire spawn Chahir made from grave robbers.

Name: Changeling (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: A race with the ability to freely shapeshift their body, their origins are shrouded in mystery. Some sources say they are fey, while others have them as descendants of Doppelgangers. No matter which origin you believe, the Changelings are unrivaled when it comes to disguising their form and using that to their advantage.

Name: Chansey
Summary: Happiny, the Playhouse Pokémon, is another baby Pokémon often found carrying around a round white stone, often seen just playing around.

Name: Chaos Beast
Summary: Chaos Beasts are formless creatures created from the raw chaos of the cosmos, constantly shifting form, inchoate and nightmarish. They rarely focus on combat, and instead are known to transform their victims to formless goop with their touch.

Name: Chitauri (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: The Chitauri are a race of cybernetically enhanced aliens who serve under the leadership of Thanos, who gave them over to Loki for use in his invasion of Earth in an attempt to acquire the Tesseract. Though they successfully invaded the planet through a wormhole created by the Tesseract, they were ultimately defeated by the Avengers.

Name: Chuul
Summary: Chuuls are the creations of the mighty abeloths created by twisting normal marine life so that they could have servants on the land. All chuuls are the creations of these eldritch aquatic creatures, and have survived since the fall of the Aboleth's empire, constantly growing.

Name: Clayface (Basil Karlo) (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Originally an horror actor driven mad after learning that Hollywood producers had untaken a remake of what was consisted as his most famous film he starred in The Terror, Basil Karlo would don a clay mask to reprise his old moniker of Clayface. After his exposure and defeat at the hands of Batman and Robin, Basil would be broken out by one of his successors, Sondra Fuller, to be part of her group of other villains using the same title in order to defeat a common goal, that being the Bat. However, Basil had another goal in mind beyond this, that being stealing the powers of the other members of the Mud Pack in order to become the Ultimate Clayface. After successence in this goal, he would become a recurring foe for the Bat-Family as well as other groups such as the Outsiders.

Name: Clayface (Post-Flashpoint)
Summary: In a search for attention, Basil Karlo spent several years attempting to become an accomplished actor to no avail. Disappointed in his lack of success he turned to working for the crime boss Penguin, who gave him a special clay that once powered the grounds of a Navajo tribe in return. The clay overtook and rewrote his entire body, turning him into Clayface.

Name: Clayface (Preston Payne) (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Born acromegalic, Preston Payne was frequently mocked and ridiculed by his peers at a young age. However, what he lacked in appearance, he made up for in his exceptionally acute intellect, graduating at the top of his class and quickly securing a job at S.T.A.R Labs. Desperate to cure his physical deformities, Payne sought out the world's foremost cosmetic surgeons but to no anvil, until he learnt of the shapeshifting Matt Hagen. Using his blood, Preston would develop and brilliant serum that would seemingly allow him to remould the very thing he despised the most, however, instead it would drive him insane, turning him into the third bearer of the mantle of Clayface.

Name: Clefairy
Summary: Clefairy is a peculiar and friendly Pokémon often seen at night in mountains dancing to the moon.

Name: Cleveland-class Light Cruiser
Summary: The Cleveland-class light cruisers were built for the U.S. Navy during World War II, and were the most numerous class of light cruisers ever built. The ships were designed with the goal of increased cruising range, anti-aircraft armament, torpedo protection, etc., compared with earlier U.S. cruisers. Fifty-two ships of this class were originally planned, but nine of them were completed as the light aircraft carriers of the Independence class, and two of them were completed to a somewhat different design, called the Fargo class. The Fargo-class cruisers were a modified version of the previous Cleveland-class cruiser design; the main difference was a more compact pyramidal superstructure with single trunked funnel, intended to improve the arcs of fire of the anti-aircraft guns. In all, 13 Fargo-class ships were planned but only Fargo and Huntington were ever completed, the rest being cancelled at varying states of completion with the de-escalation of World War II. Of the 27 Cleveland-class cruisers that were commissioned, one (Galveston) was completed as a guided missile cruiser and five were later modified as Galveston and Providence-class guided missile cruisers. Following the naming convention at the time, all the ships completed as cruisers were named for US cities and towns.

Name: Cloud Giant
Summary: Second tallest of the true Giants, the Cloud Giants are an aloof race, viewing all others barring Storm Giants as beneath them- fitting, given their proclivity to reside in castles which float on clouds. Alongside their impressive physical strength they have innate magical abilities, being able to levitate objects among other things.

Name: Colleen Wing (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Colleen Wing is a skilled martial artist who was trained by the mysterious Bakuto. She would later open up her own dojo in New York City. Colleen would eventually meet Danny Rand and help him adjust to the changes that had occurred in the city since his disappearance 15 years prior.

Name: Condiment King (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Mitchell Mayo, once an average guy went inexplicably crazy and donned the identity of the Condiment King to cause crime. He was shown tormenting multiple policemen with his special designed sauce, until he was swiftly defeated by Batgirl and Robin. He was then taken to Arkham Asylum, where he eventually was able to work in the kitchen and fuel his obsession, as well as improve upon his formula. This was further aided by Poison Ivy, who taught him vast knowledge on roots, herbs, and spices. Years later, he would get out of Arkham and be "jokerized". Jokerization is stated to amplify the infected's personality, which actually made Mitchell a credible threat. This would almost cause the Birds of Prey to lose to him, as they though he was a joke. It is later stated due to the nature of Condiment King's obsession/portrayal as a joke, juries and parole boards don't take him seriously, thus allowing him to be set free on Gotham again and again. During Final Crisis Aftermath, Mitchell was one of Immortus' followers, The Army of the Endangered, and was cybernetically enhanced by the brilliant Professor Achilles Milo. He was the one to introduce the "Human Flame" to the group, which would be a mistake. Human Flame would rebel, and along with Seductress, kill every member of The Army of the Endangered, including Mitchell.

Name: Constantine Drakon (Post-Crisis)
Summary: As a child of ten, Constantine Drakon was often bullied by others for his diminutive stature, until he found his masterful skill in murder, and has become an unparalleled assassin-for-hire and a foe to Green Arrow

Name: Corvus Glaive (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Corvus Glaive was one of Thanos' children, and a member of the Black Order. After retrieving the Space Stone with Thanos and his siblings, Corvus Glaive and Proxima Midnight traveled to Scotland and ambushed Vision and Scarlet Witch. Corvus Glaive tried to take the Mind Stone, but Captain America, Falcon, and Black Widow arrived, and he was wounded by Black Widow. Corvus Glaive attempted to take the Mind Stone from Vision in Wakanda later. However, he was killed by Vision, who used his own weapon to stab him in the back.

Name: Couatl
Summary: In the beginning of civilization there were five creator races, and the mightiest of these were the Saruukh, who enslaved the other four. Eventually their empire spread so wide that it became too thin, and the vast majority of those in power were not sarrukh. And so the empire fell.

Name: Crossbones (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Brock Rumlow was a HYDRA infiltrator who had been posing as a S.H.I.E.L.D. agent, and STRIKE's team field commander. Due to his training from S.H.I.E.L.D. and HYDRA, Rumlow had become a world-class combatant, with extensive experience in street fighting, martial arts, and military combat techniques.

Name: Crossbones (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Captain America: I have this theory that no one is totally beyond redemption. That's why I'm so big on preserving life-- Even the lives of those who try to kill me. As long as a person's alive, there's hope he may redeem himself. So what I'm saying is... even though you've acted like lowlife scum every time we've met, there must be something good about you... Love for your mother, a childhood pet, a woman maybe? I'd really like to know what it is. Crossbones: You wanna know where I'm soft, huh, Cappy? Ha! Okay, why not? I'll tell you. I love... TO HATE! HAHAHAHAHAHA!

Name: Crypt Chanter
Summary: Corpse Chanters are malignant, ghostly undead known to haunt tombs, mausoleums, crypts, and similar places, filling their empty halls with their eerie music. Here, they disarm those that might disturb the dead, singing beautiful and terrifying songs to the interlopers, drawing them to their deaths.

Name: Ctenmiir
Summary: Once a great dwarven warrior, Ctenmiir fell in battle to a vampire and became one himself. After his vampire master died by the hand of Keraptis he swore loyalty to the later, with the wizard tasking him to protect the legendary weapon Whelm which Ctenmiir wielded before his death.

Name: CV90
Summary: The Combat Vehicle 90 (CV90) (Swedish: stridsfordon 90ⓘ, strf 90 or Stridsfordon 90) is a family of Swedish tracked armoured combat vehicles designed by the Swedish Defence Materiel Administration (FMV), Hägglund & Söner and Bofors during the mid-1980s to early 1990s, before entering service in Sweden in the mid-1990s. The CV90 platform design has continuously evolved from the Mk 0 to the current Mk IV with technological advances and changing battlefield requirements.

Name: D-Man (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Dennis Dunphy was a high school athlete who was given super strength by the mysterious Power Broker, and he joined the new Unlimited Class Wrestling Federation (UCWF), where he could use his augmented strength against other similarly augmented wrestlers, and he became close friends with the Thing, under the ring name Demolition Dunphy.

Name: Daken Akihiro
Summary: Akihiro, codename Daken is a fictional character appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. Daken is the mutant son of Wolverine and his deceased wife Itsu. He possesses superhuman abilities similar to his father (e.g., healing factor, retractable claws), and was a member of the Dark Avengers under the name Wolverine until the conclusion of the 2010 storyline, "Siege". Daken was ranked sixth in Comics Alliance's "50 Sexiest Male Characters in Comics" list and is often recognized for his sex appeal

Name: Daku
Summary: Daku is the King of the Insect Enterrans and one of the Seven Enterran Generals. He resembles a Hercules Beetle-knight.

Name: Daredevil (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Born in the historically gritty or crime-ridden, working-class Irish-American neighborhood of Hell's Kitchen in New York City, Matthew "Matt" Michael Murdock is blinded by a radioactive substance that falls from a truck after he pushes a man to safety from the oncoming vehicle. While he no longer can see, the radioactive exposure heightens his remaining senses beyond normal human ability and gives him a "radar sense". His father, a boxer named Jack Murdock, supports him as he grows up, though Jack is later killed by gangsters after refusing to throw a fight. After donning a yellow and dark red costume (later all dark red), Matt seeks out revenge against his father's killers as the superhero Daredevil, fighting against his many enemies, including Bullseye and Kingpin.

Name: Death (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Alice Wu-Gulliver: So.. you’re a- a green witch? Rio Vidal: Um… less a green witch, more, the Green Witch.

Name: Deathstroke (Post-Crisis)
Summary: Deathstroke (Slade Joseph Wilson) is a fictional supervillain appearing in American comic books published by DC Comics. He is a mercenary and assassin who serves as the archenemy of the Teen Titans, specifically Dick Grayson. Over the years, writers have developed him as an adversary of other superheroes in the DC universe as well, such as Batman and Green Arrow.

Name: Deathstroke (Post-Flashpoint)
Summary: Slade Joseph Wilson, aka Deathstroke, joined the military at age sixteen, was an exceptional soldier and earned his fair share of medals. He volunteered for "Project X", which granted him enhanced reflexes, strength, mental capacity and rapid healing. After going AWOL in Bosnia, and winning his signature sword, he took on its name and began running covert black bag missions. It wasn't until after the death of his son that he became the world's deadliest assassin.

Name: Deep Gnome
Summary: Deep Gnomes, also known as Svirfneblin, are Gnomes primarily found underground in the Underdark. Their time in the underground has made so they naturally blend in and understand stone. They possess both great fighting skills and innate magical abilities, which they use greatly in combat.

Name: Defenders (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: The Defenders were a team of four street-based superheroes who banded together to save New York City from the Hand.

Name: Delver
Summary: Delvers are sub-subterranean creatures that use their acidic, corrosive slime to burrow through the earth, devouring stone for its minerals to sustain itself. They are predatory towards earthen creatures such as the common Xorn, though are largely docile outside of that (hostile specimens are recorded to have existed).

Name: Dervill the Treacherous
Summary: Dervill was a court wizard of Rhoona, serving his duke faithfully until the arrival of Xanathon in the city. With the rise of his temple's power, Dervill shifted his allegiance to that of Xanathon, believing him the probable winner of the upcoming conflict.

Name: Destrachan
Summary: Destrachans are dungeon dwelling creatures known for their immense control over sound- specifically, their ears are adjustable to various settings of sound. They look beastly and unintelligent, though this is not the case- in fact, they are crafty sadists, always looking for more prey in a very competitive food chain. Their roars are known to shatter stone walls, making them a powerful threat in the average dungeon.

Name: Detective Chimp (Post-Flashpoint)
Summary: Bobo T. Chimpanzee, the Detective Chimpanzee, used to be a normal circus animal, until an unlikely series of events led to him drinking from a magical fountain that augmented his mind to an incredible level of intelligence and gifted him immortality.

Name: Deva
Summary: Devas are messengers of the Good-aligned deities that they serve, generally taking the role of spreading goodness in the lesser planes in the name of their gods- either a subtle humanoid or an animal. When they need to they cast off their guise of mortality and appear in their true godly beauty.

Name: Diamondback (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Willis Stryker, also known as Diamondback, is the half brother of Luke Cage and a deadly criminal equipped with advanced weaponry from Hammer Industries.

Name: Dire Bear
Summary: A regular bear is already a dangerous beast to stumble upon in the wild, thus a Dire Bear is an even worst meetup one can have in the forest due to it being a vastly stronger bear which can easily maul adventurers to death if they're not careful.

Name: Dire Boar
Summary: The Dire Boar is a giant variant of the regular boar, it's a rather vicious animal who when engages in combat attempts to tear its enemies into shreds with its tusks. The Dire Boar has 2 variants, the Thunderfury Boar which is a Fey Dire Boar and the Fhorge which is a variant found in the Outlands.

Name: Dire Elk
Summary: A bigger version of an elk, the Dire Elk is a rather aggressive and will try to gore its enemies with its massive antlers. It's incredibly rare, to the point where people believe that sighting is a foreshadowing of important events such as the birth of a king.

Name: Dire Rhinoceros
Summary: Larger and stronger than its regular counterpart, the Dire Rhinoceros is most often found in cold environments and is a formidable opponent for anyone who tries to challenge it.

Name: Dire Tiger
Summary: A far larger and stronger version of a tiger, the Dire Tiger is also a fearsome ambush predator which lives in dense jungles.

Name: Dire Tortoise
Summary: Large and slow, this tortoise travels in the desert eating any plants it can find and attacking anything it sees due to its bad temper

Name: Django Freeman
Summary: Tier: 10-A. 9-C with firearms. 8-C with preparation

Name: Doctor Strange (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Thor: So, Earth has wizards now? Strange: The preferred term is "Master of the Mystic Arts".

Name: Domino (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Neena "Domino" Thurman is a character from Marvel Comics. She is best known as a member of the X-Force. Domino made her first full main story appearance in X-Force #8 as a unique individual from the Wild Pack group driven by the mutant Cable.

Name: Dragon Turtle
Summary: Dragon Turtles are immense aquatic creatures with genetic ties to true dragons. Many cultures regarded Dragon Turtles as the most dangerous monsters of the sea, whilst others worshiped them as a sign of the gods. Despite not being the strongest of all sea monsters, they were held as posing a significantly higher threat due to their tendency to attack and rip apart ships passing through their territories. The turtles were obsessed with treasure and could often be bribed or given tribute to receive desired effects ranging from simply leaving ships alone to attacking others.

Name: Dryad (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: Dryads are forest spirits and guardians of the plants within them, generally residing within the trees. Dryads are peaceful by nature (though not unwilling to fight), and are often considered to be exemplary messengers of the gods- including the likes of Corellon Larethian and Erevan Ilesere.

Name: Electivire
Summary: Electivire is a Gen IV Pokémon and the evolution of the Gen I Electabuzz, and the final form of the Gen II Elekid. It evolves when traded with an Electrizer.

Name: Elektra (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Elektra Natchios is an assassin who was trained under Stick to join the Chaste. She fell in love with Matt Murdock during a mission for Stick to bring Murdock into the organization. She returned to his life after years of absence, putting her beliefs and methods at conflict with his own. Later, she was revealed to potentially be the Black Sky, the one who is supposed to lead the Hand. However, Elektra chose to help Murdock defeat the malevolent organization, and was killed in the final confrontation with Nobu Yoshioka. The Hand then retrieved Elektra's corpse from the grave and placed it in a stone chamber to be exposed to the Resurrection Elixir.

Name: Elephant (Dungeons and Dragons)
Summary: One of the many options for a mount animal, the Elephant is a large herbivore people in Dungeons And Dragons can use. They are extremely large and rather smart for an animal, being able to avoid attacking objects that will harm them if touched.

Name: Elsa Bloodstone (Marvel Comics)
Summary: Elsa Bloodstone is the daughter of the immortal monster hunter, Ulysses Bloodstone, who follows her father's footsteps to be a monster hunter herself. Armed with an arsenal of rifles, shotguns, pistols and other weapons, alongside being imbued by the power of the Bloodgem thanks to her choker, she hunts the various beasts and creatures of the Marvel Universe with expertise.

Name: Erik Killmonger (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
Summary: Erik Stevens (born N'Jadaka) was a former American black-ops soldier of Wakandan origin through his father, Prince N'Jobu. His savagery while serving in the US black-ops earned him the nickname Erik Killmonger. Years after T'Chaka killed his father for betraying Wakanda, Killmonger then planned to forcibly dethrone T'Challa in order to accomplish his father's plan to use Wakanda's technology to conquer the world via imperialistic, supremacist, world-spanning, and likely genocidal warfare, to stop what he perceived to be the oppression of people of African descent by the world. Manipulating and then killing Ulysses Klaue to gain access to their city, Killmonger seemingly killed T'Challa during ritual combat and took the throne, but just before Killmonger unleashed his plan, the Black Panther had returned and challenged Killmonger, eventually killing him in their final battle.

Name: Ethereal Ooze
Summary: The Ethereal Ooze is an ooze found in the Ethereal plane, it uses its ability to freely travel to the Prime Material world to snatch unsuspecting prey into the Ethereal plane and eat them.

Name: F-117 Nighthawk
Summary: The F-117 Nighthawk is a single seat, twin engine attack aircraft developed by the secretive Skunk Works division of Lockheed and operated chiefly by the USAF. The aircraft is based on the earlier Have Blue technology demonstrator and was the first operational aircraft to be designed around stealth technology.

Name: F-14 Tomcat
Summary: The F-14 Tomcat is a supersonic, twin-engine, variable sweep wing, two-place fighter designed to attack and destroy enemy aircraft at night and in all weather conditions. Although now retired in the U.S. Navy, it remains in use, seeing service with the Iranian Air Force.

Name: F-15 Eagle
Summary: The F-15 is a fighter aircraft currently serving in the United States Air Force, and several other air forces around the world. Created in response to a satelite photograph of the MiG-25, to this day it remains one of the primary fighters of the USAF, having served over 3 decades with a combat record including 104 enemy aircraft shot down, 1 satellite, no air-to-air losses of its own, and only 3 confirmed losses from groundfire.

Name: F-35 Lightning II
Summary: The F-35 Lightning II is family of single-seat, single-engine, all-weather stealth multi-role fighters developed and manufactured by Lockheed Martin for the Joint Strike Fighter program. The fifth-generation combat aircraft is designed to perform ground-attack and air-superiority missions.

Name: F-86 Sabre
Summary: The North American F-86 Sabre was a fighter used by the US and it's allies during the early Cold War period, and saw military service in the Korean War. It's closest Soviet equivalent is the MiG-15, and often saw combat against it during the Korean War. The aircraft was finally retired in 1994 in Bolivia, 47 years after it has made it's first flight and 45 years after it first entered service with the USAF.

Name: F/A-18 Hornet
Summary: The F/A-18 Hornet is a twin engine all-weather carrier capable multirole fighter developed and designed by McDonnell Douglas (Now Boeing) and Northrop. It was derived from the earlier YF-17 design designed by the latter in the 1970s for use by the US Navy and Marine Corps. It has also seen service in use by several other nations, and first flew in 1978, entering service for the first time in 1983.

Name: Falcon (Marvel Cinematic Universe)
